Europe Needs a Migration Restart
Brussels — Over 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
Meanwhile, the rescue ships Open Arms and Ocean Viking have been searching all summer for safe ports of entry for their passengers.
Refugee and migrant camps on Lesbos Island in Greece are overcrowded, and the conditions in other Libyan reception camps are similar.
Turkey has renounced the 2016 agreement that prevented migrants from entering the EU.
Although Europe wants to help immigrants and respects international law, it does not want to be overcrowded.
In 2015–16, the number of refugees and migrants entering the EU surged — many fleeing the Syrian conflict — which greatly affected trust within the EU.
A massive influx of migrants eroded confidence in the management of external EU borders and asylum, and highlighted the lack of effective cooperation with migrant-sending countries.
Therefore, migration has become a political football, a favorite topic for populists.
Under the leadership of President von der Leyen, the new European Commission must reassert control over migration issues while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
For this, the EU needs to revise four aspects of its policies and mobilize member states to take action for the benefit of Europe.
First, the EU must urgently secure its external borders, which is a prerequisite for keeping internal borders open.
Any country where people can move freely internally, including the United States, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia, will not outsource external border control to a state or region.
Controlling the EU's external borders must be a collective task, as well as a national task.
The European Border and Coast Guard Agency Frontex must be further strengthened and should deploy joint guard units with member states — including along coastlines and airports.
The EU also needs to restart Operation Sophia to combat illegal immigration in the Mediterranean.
Secondly, Europe needs to address economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Mixing them together has led the asylum system to the brink of collapse; addressing them separately would help ensure that migrants concerned about their safety can voice their concerns under protected rights.
Solving the EU's real economic and social needs requires an effective blue card or green card policy for economic migrants, and the implementation of an overall immigration target.
This cannot wait for the next immigration crisis to introduce these mechanisms.
To achieve this, the EU must break the taboo.
First, the number of economic migrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a matter of common interest.
Second, policies must clearly define which migrants are welcome.
Third, member states must answer the question of what kind of EU assistance is needed to achieve a smooth migration process.
Finally, visas and work permits must be made public to facilitate the return of illegal migrants to their countries of origin.
Admittedly, according to the EU treaties, each member state needs to manage migration from outside the EU on its own.
However, it would be a major step forward if the government reached an agreement on the overall EU immigration target.
In return, member states could specify the source countries and specific criteria for economic migrants they wish to receive, as well as the EU budget resources needed to accommodate them.
In this way, the right to receive immigrants would become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has long implemented an active immigration policy, selecting immigrants based on indicators such as source countries, skill levels, and age groups.
Europe can also do this.
Third, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
First, the mandatory one-size-fits-all requirement for distributing asylum seekers within the EU must be abolished.
This requirement undermines the atmosphere within the EU, but it could still be feasible if the border, asylum, and immigration system were fully effective.
Additionally, the frontline member states of the EU cannot be expected to solve the problem of illegal migration across external borders on their own.
The reception centers are already overcrowded, and the immigrants are subjected to abuse by the authorities or are driven north.
The responsibility of the first member state the immigrants arrive in must be supplemented by the EU's cohesion policy.
The EU must also provide experts and funding to improve the behavior and management capacity of national asylum institutions.
Only in this way can national decisions be respected throughout the Schengen area, ensuring the integrity of the cross-border travel zone.
After improving the behavior and management capacity of national asylum institutions, the asylum application processing procedures can also be shared among member states.
The fourth point is that the EU should build stronger mutually beneficial cooperation with source and transit countries.
These links are crucial to repatriating migrants who are legally prohibited from entering the EU.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should mobilize all diplomatic tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as programs in security, trade, energy, agriculture, fishing, climate action, aviation, and health.
The EU's migration objectives, as well as skill cooperation for European jobs, can be offered to third countries seeking stable remittances.
At the same time, the EU must address the root causes of migration.
This includes population explosion in Sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; disease outbreaks; racial conflicts; and lack of job opportunities.
The EU's aid should focus on restoring stability and reducing risks by supporting security, community resilience, and good governance.
Success in this area could make investments safer, unlock private and domestic finance, thereby achieving national economic growth, job creation, and providing an alternative to migration.
The new European Commission has an opportunity to move the EU away from an unconscious reaction to the migration crisis, towards a more coherent and sustained approach, regardless of internal or external contexts.
We must never miss this opportunity.
